    "leafs": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Maple Leafs",
      "league": "NHL",
      "record": "32-36-14",
      "detail": "8th in Atlantic Division",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "Another season of what-ifs and near-misses has mercifully ended for Toronto. The Maple Leafs finished 32-36-14, eighth in the Atlantic Division, 31 points behind a playoff spot, their seven-game losing streak the final punctuation on a season that never found its footing. Seventy-eight points. Fifteenth in the entire league. This is not the trajectory of a franchise built to compete - it's the record of a team that lost its way and never recovered it.\n\n<strong>The collapse was both swift and inevitable, a season that promised so much in October deteriorating into a lottery-bound March and April.</strong> When your team finishes this far out of contention, the postmortem isn't about individual games or missed opportunities. It's about systemic failure - personnel decisions that didn't age well, a roster construction that left the margin for error razor-thin, and a coaching staff that couldn't arrest the decline when it mattered most.\n\nNow comes the hard part: accountability. <strong>Expect significant changes in the front office and behind the bench this summer; this organization cannot afford another season of this magnitude.</strong> The draft lottery looms. Free agency beckons. Toronto needs to decide whether to tear down or retool - and do it before next October arrives.",
        "updated": "Updated April 20, 2026"
      },
