    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "8-13",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays came to Arizona looking for oxygen, and for one glorious inning on Saturday night, they found it. <strong>Eight runs in the first - a franchise-tying explosion that knocked Diamondbacks starter Ryne Nelson clean out of the game</strong> - felt like the kind of cathartic release a team drowning at 8-13 desperately needed. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. and Kazuma Okamoto supplied the thunderous doubles. Nine of the first ten hitters reached base. It was baseball the way Toronto remembers it.\n\nThen reality reasserted itself. The Jays won that game 10-4, snapping a four-game losing streak, but couldn't hold the momentum. They lost the series finale 6-2, and now sit fourth in the AL East, 4.5 games back with a record that screams crisis. One win in their last five games. Eleven playoff seeds away from October. The franchise record first inning was a mirage - a reminder of what they're capable of when the bats wake up, not a turning point.\n\n<strong>The Angels come to town Tuesday night. Toronto needs consistency, not fireworks. One inning of magic doesn't rebuild a season.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated April 20, 2026"
      },
